{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-collection-tsx","path":"/collections/collection_639/","result":{"pageContext":{"collection":{"collection_id":"collection_639","scd_publish_status":null,"record_type":"individual recording","collection_content_category":["Recorded Sound Materials"],"collection_title":"William Mayer","collection_description":"Martin Bookspan interviews American contemporary composer William Mayer. Mayer talks about his studies at Yale University with Herbert Baumgartner; about his career as a composer; about his work with pianist William Masselos; and about his son pianist Stephen Mayer. Speaking about the variety of music he composed, Mayer says that he prefers to write show music. He speaks about his work as a treasurer for CRI (Composers Recordings, Inc.). The composer discusses in detail each of the following works, excerpts of which are then played during the interview: Octagon (for piano and orchestra, fifth and seventh movements) (1971), Piano sonata (first movement) (1959) that he composed in twelve-tone technique, Two news items: Hastily formed contemporary music ensemble reveals origins (for soprano and instrumental ensemble), Brass quintet (1965), Messages (for flute, string trio, and percussion) (1973), and Two pastels for orchestra.","collection_holder_category":["Municipal"],"collection_holder_name":["New York Public Library for the Performing Arts, Dorothy and Lewis B. Cullman Center"],"collection_holder_city":"New York","collection_holder_state":"New York","collection_holder_country":"United States","content_types":["Interviews"],"dates":null,"extent":"1 recording","historical_relevance":"Broadcast on radio station WNYC, New York, N.Y., Jan. 22, 1973.","physical_formats":null,"access_statement":null,"finding_aid_url":"http://catalog.nypl.org/search~S1?/X%28%28radio%29+and+%28broadcast%29%29&searchscope=1&Da=1919&Db=1981&m=p&m=m&m=q&m=-&m=y&m=j&SORT=D/X%28%28radio%29+and+%28broadcast%29%29&searchscope=1&Da=1919&Db=1981&m=